ROOT CAUSE: `/mnt/c/Users/Owner/OneDrive/Documents/Classes/COS/COS484/chatdbgpro/bench/cases/paper/test-use-after-free/program.cpp:10-11` corrupts the only owning pointer before deletion: `new int(100)` returns the allocation base, observed as `0x502000000010`, but `n--` changes `n` to `0x50200000000c`, four bytes before the allocated `int`. The stopped program is in `operator delete`/ASan deallocation at line 11 with `n == 0x50200000000c`, so `delete n;` is not being passed the exact pointer returned by `new`; that is undefined behavior and ASan crashes/reports it before the later intended dangling dereference at `doSomething(n)`. If execution continued past that, `doSomething(n)` and `std::cout << *n` would also be invalid because `n` would either point before the allocation or to freed storage.

LOCAL FIX: Preserve the allocation pointer and do not use it after deletion; perform the work while the object is still alive, then delete exactly the pointer returned by `new`. For example: ```diff
 int main()
 {
   int * n = new int(100);
-  n--;
-  delete n;
   char * ch = new char[16];
   delete [] ch;
   doSomething(n);
   std::cout << "n = " << *n << std::endl;
+  delete n;
   return 0;
 }
``` This removes the invalid pointer decrement, avoids deleting a non-base address, and ensures `doSomething(n)` and `*n` occur before `delete n`.

GLOBAL FIX: Replace raw owning pointers with RAII ownership types so pointer arithmetic and manual lifetime mistakes are not possible at the call site, e.g. use `auto n = std::make_unique<int>(100); doSomething(n.get()); std::cout << "n = " << *n << std::endl;` and `std::array<char, 16>` or `std::vector<char>` for the character buffer. More broadly, separate ownership from access by passing `int&` or a non-owning bounded/view type to `doSomething` instead of a raw mutable pointer, and maintain the invariant that only owning RAII objects release memory while borrowed references/views cannot delete or outlive the owner.

